primary_diagnosis.name: Bronchitis

differential_diagnoses.name: Pneumonia

differential_diagnoses.name: Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD)
differential_diagnoses.reasoning: Although COPD can cause chronic cough and fatigue, the acute onset and lack of a history of smoking or environmental exposure make bronchitis a more likely diagnosis.

primary_diagnosis.name: Upper Respiratory Infection (URI)
primary_diagnosis.reasoning: Persistent cough and fatigue are common symptoms of a URI. Given the duration of 3 weeks, it could be a prolonged viral infection or a secondary bacterial infection.

differential_diagnoses.name: Acute Bronchitis
differential_diagnoses.reasoning: Similar symptoms to URI, but involves inflammation of the bronchial tubes. The persistent cough points towards this possibility.

differential_diagnoses.name: Pneumonia
differential_diagnoses.reasoning: Pneumonia can present with cough and fatigue. Less likely without fever or shortness of breath, but needs to be ruled out.

differential_diagnoses.name: Influenza
differential_diagnoses.reasoning: Influenza can cause cough and fatigue. The prolonged duration makes it less likely, but a complicated or secondary infection following influenza is possible.

differential_diagnoses.name: Chronic Fatigue Syndrome
differential_diagnoses.reasoning: Fatigue is a prominent symptom, but usually accompanied by other symptoms beyond just cough. Less likely given the acute onset.

diagnostic_tests.purpose: Rule out pneumonia or other lung pathology.
Identify any bacterial infection if cough is productive.
Assess for signs of infection (elevated white blood cell count).
Rule out active influenza or COVID-19 infection

immediate_actions: Monitor for worsening symptoms (e.g., shortness of breath, high fever)

medications.rationale: Expectorant to help loosen mucus and ease cough.
Cough suppressant to help reduce cough frequency, especially at night.

consultations.reason: If symptoms persist or worsen despite initial management or if chest x-ray is abnormal.

patient_education: Proper cough etiquette to prevent spread of infection
When to seek immediate medical attention (red flags)
Avoid smoking or exposure to irritants.

follow_up.conditions: Worsening cough, fever, shortness of breath, chest pain.
